				\begin{document}$${\rm{score}} = Intercept + \sum\limits_{i = 1}^n {{\rm{coefficients}}[i] \times } Feature[i]$$\end{document}

Based on the theory of transfer learning (TL), we selected the Swin Transformer DL network, which was pre-trained on the ImageNet dataset, as the foundational model for the DL model in this study. The Swin Transformer utilized the Patch Partition image segmentation module to divide the RGB image of H×W into independent patches, with each patch’s feature being a series of the original pixel RGB values. The Patch Embeding maps these original feature values to any dimension and ultimately processes the image size as \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${H \over 4} \times {W \over 4} \times C$$\end{document}. After each Patch Merging layer, both H and W dimensions of the image were reduced to half of their previous sizes, while the feature channel was expanded by 2 times (Supplementary data, Figure S1). We initially cropped out ROIs from 2DUS and CEUS images and normalize pixels to a range between 0 and 255. All input images were converted to 3-channel RBG format and resized to a size of 224 × 224 × 3. Subsequently, we input the ROIs of 2DUS images, the ROIs of CEUS images, and the ROIs combining both into the network; then we used the output probability from the network as our classification result. As such, different DL models were obtained, including DL_2DUS model, DL_CEUS model and DL_2D_CEUS model.
